==English==
===Etymology===
From Old French ''[[amirer]]'', later from French ''[[admirer]]'' or Latin ''[[admirari]]'', which comes from ''[[ad-]]'' + ''[[mirari]]'' "to wonder".

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: [[WEAE]] /ædˈmaɪ.ɚ/
IPA: [[RP]] /ədˈmaɪə/

===Verb===
{{en-verb|admir|ing}}

# ''(transitive)'' To [[regard]] with [[wonder]] and [[delight]]; to look upon with an [[elevated]] feeling of [[pleasure]], as something which calls out [[approbation]], [[esteem]], [[love]] or [[reverence]]; to [[estimate]] or [[prize]] highly; as, to admire a person of high moral worth, to admire a landscape.

